# cPanel: FTP Accounts

## Create FTP Account

- Login to cPanel of your account
- Under Files click on FTP Accounts

```diagram

```

- Put your username, password, Directory path and select the quota of the ftp account
If you enter the top-level of the web site by entering a slash (/), all users with the correct password will be able to add, edit, and delete all files on your site. 
In order to avoid it limit an FTP account to a smaller sections of your web site.

```diagram

```

- After you added all necessary details then click on Create FTP Account and you are DONE


## How to Modify an FTP account in cPanel

- Login to cPanel of your account
- Under Files click on FTP Accounts

```diagram

```

- Scroll down. You should now see existing FTP Accounts Under FTP Accounts

```diagram

```

- Under Actions, you can perform actions like password/quota change of ftp account, delete and ftp account.


## How to configure my FTP client (Filezilla FTP client) to upload/download files

- Login to cpanel of your website
- Click on FTP Accounts under Files Menu
- You should now see existing FTP Accounts FTP Accounts
- Click on configure FTP client , next to the FTP user for which you want to configure FTP client.

```diagram

```

- Click on FTP Configuration File link to configure your FIlezilla FTP client

- Once clicked on it , it will ask you to download .xml file save it and open it with your filezilla FTP client

## Upload my webpages / files on my cpanel account using FTP

- On your local machine install Filezilla FTP client. Vidoe Tutorial
- Now Run the Filezilla FTP client
- At your left hand top side, in the host field, enter your website name / ip address.
- In the username field enter your cpanel username of your website and password.
- Leave the port field blank or you can set the FTP port at 21
- Now click on Quick connect

```diagram

```

- Once you got connected, at your left hand side panel the files that are listed that is your local PC and your right hand side panel should be showing files that are hosted on your cpanel account

```diagram

```

- On your right hand side panel double click on public_html folder, this is where you have to upload your webpages.
- Now you need to do is find the files you want to upload on the LEFT side of the screen and drag them to the RIGHT. This will then upload the files to your website.

## How to Enable/Disable Anonymous FTP

**What is Anonymous FTP**

Anonymous FTP allows anyone FTP connections to customer site, to upload or download files, without having to log in with a username and password.

Anonymous FTP access is controlled through Anonymous FTP in cPanel. Settings allow customer to enable or disable anonymous access at any time. Customer can allow uploading to any particular folder created in the public_ftp directory of their account.

> Allowing anonymous access to account may present a security risk.
> Customer can set up individual users with an ftp account and allow access to particular directories or the site as a whole. This may be preferable to allowing anonymous access.
{.is-warning}


**Anonymous FTP Enable/Disable**

1. Enable
 - Login to cPanel
 - Click Anonymous FTP under section named Files
 
```diagram

```
 
- Select Allow anonymous access to ftp://ftp.yourdomain.com
- Select Allow anonymous uploads to ftp://ftp.yourdomain.com/incoming
- Both boxes must be checked to allow uploading of files.
- Save Settings.
- Anonymous FTP Welcome Message is optional. Type in the box a message or instructions for your users when they log into your public_ftp folder.
- Save Settings.

```diagram

```

2. **Disable**
  - Remove the checks from appropriate boxes.
